Here's an implementation of a queue data structure using two stacks in Java:

```java
import java.util.Stack;

public class QueueWithTwoStacks<T> {
    private Stack<T> inbox;
    private Stack<T> outbox;

    public QueueWithTwoStacks() {
        inbox = new Stack<T>();
        outbox = new Stack<T>();
    }

    public void enqueue(T item) {
        inbox.push(item);
    }

    public T dequeue() {
        if (outbox.isEmpty()) {
            while (!inbox.isEmpty()) {
                outbox.push(inbox.pop());
            }
        }

        return outbox.pop();
    }

    public boolean isEmpty() {
        return inbox.isEmpty() && outbox.isEmpty();
    }
}
```

In this implementation, there are two stacks, `inbox` and `outbox`. Elements are enqueued by pushing them onto the `inbox`. When a dequeue operation is performed, if the `outbox` is empty, elements are popped from the `inbox` and pushed onto the `outbox`, which puts the elements in the correct order for a dequeue operation. The first item in the `outbox` is then popped and returned, which is the oldest element in the queue.

This implementation has O(n) time complexity for a worst-case dequeue operation, when the `outbox` is empty, but has O(1) time complexity for all subsequent dequeue operations until the `inbox` is empty. The enqueue operation always has O(1) time complexity.

