public int[] productExceptSelf(int[] nums) {
    int n = nums.length;
    int[] output = new int[n];

    // Compute the products of all elements to the left of each index
    int product = 1;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        output[i] = product;
        product *= nums[i];
    }

    // Compute the products of all elements to the right of each index
    product = 1;
    for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        output[i] *= product;
        product *= nums[i];
    }

    return output;
}
```

The idea is to first compute the products of all elements to the left of each index, and store them in `output`. Then, we compute the products of all elements to the right of each index and multiply them with the corresponding value in `output`. This gives us the product of all the elements except the one at the current index. By doing this in two passes, we avoid division and handle the cases where there are zeros in the input array.

