To find the median of two sorted arrays of size m and n respectively, we can follow the below steps:

1. First we need to ensure that the length of the first array nums1 is less than or equal to the length of the second array nums2. If it is not, we swap both arrays.

2. We can then use binary search on the smaller array nums1 and partition it into two halves, such that the partition divides the array in such a way that the elements on the left side of the partition are smaller than the elements on the right side of the partition.

3. Similarly, we partition the larger array nums2 into two halves, again ensuring that elements on the left side of the partition are smaller than the elements on the right side of the partition.

4. We calculate the median based on the partitioned arrays. If the total number of elements is odd, then the median is the maximum of the left elements in both the partitioned arrays. If the total number of elements is even, then the median is the average of the maximum of the left elements and the minimum of the right elements in both the partitioned arrays.

Below is the Python code that implements this approach:

```
def findMedianSortedArrays(nums1, nums2):
    if len(nums1) > len(nums2):
        nums1, nums2 = nums2, nums1

    m, n = len(nums1), len(nums2)
    imin, imax, half_len = 0, m, (m + n + 1) // 2

    while imin <= imax:
        i = (imin + imax) // 2
        j = half_len - i

        if i < m and nums2[j-1] > nums1[i]:
            imin = i + 1
        elif i > 0 and nums1[i-1] > nums2[j]:
            imax = i - 1
        else:
            if i == 0: max_of_left = nums2[j-1]
            elif j == 0: max_of_left = nums1[i-1]
            else: max_of_left = max(nums1[i-1], nums2[j-1])

            if (m + n) % 2 == 1:
                return float(max_of_left)

            if i == m: min_of_right = nums2[j]
            elif j == n: min_of_right = nums1[i]
            else: min_of_right = min(nums1[i], nums2[j])

            return (max_of_left + min_of_right) / 2.0
```

The time complexity of this approach is O(log(min(m,n))) as we are using binary search to partition the two arrays.

This problem can be solved using a recursive Backtracking approach. We start by iterating over the 2D board and look for the first letter of the given word. Once we find it, we recursively check the adjacent cells for the next letter of the word. We mark the current cell as visited using a boolean array and then recurse over the top, bottom, left, and right cells. If we are able to construct the entire word through this process, then we return true, else we backtrack by marking the current cell as unvisited and continuing with the next cell in the board. If all cells have been tried and we are unable to construct the word, then we return false.

Here's a sample implementation of the algorithm:

```
class Solution {
    public boolean exist(char[][] board, String word) {
        int rows = board.length;
        int cols = board[0].length;
        boolean[][] visited = new boolean[rows][cols];
        for (int i = 0; i < rows; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < cols; j++) {
                if (board[i][j] == word.charAt(0) && backtrack(board, visited, i, j, word, 0)) {
                    return true;
                }
            }
        }
        return false;
    }

    private boolean backtrack(char[][] board, boolean[][] visited, int i, int j, String word, int index) {
        if (index == word.length()) {
            return true;
        }
        if (i < 0 || i >= board.length || j < 0 || j >= board[0].length || visited[i][j] || board[i][j] != word.charAt(index)) {
            return false;
        }
        visited[i][j] = true;
        boolean found = backtrack(board, visited, i + 1, j, word, index + 1)
                        || backtrack(board, visited, i - 1, j, word, index + 1)
                        || backtrack(board, visited, i, j + 1, word, index + 1)
                        || backtrack(board, visited, i, j - 1, word, index + 1);
        visited[i][j] = false;
        return found;
    }
}
``` 

This implementation has a time complexity of O(M*N*3^k), where M is the number of rows, N is the number of columns, and k is the length of the word. The factor of 3^k is because for every cell, there are at most 3 directions to continue exploring. The space complexity is also O(M*N) because we use a boolean array to mark visited cells.

To solve this problem, we can use dynamic programming. We create a 2D boolean array dp where dp[i][j] represents whether the first i characters of s1 and the first j characters of s2 can form the first (i+j) characters of s3. 

We initialize dp[0][0] to be true because an empty s1 and s2 can form an empty s3. We then fill out the rest of the first row and first column of dp, which represents the case when one of s1 or s2 is empty. If dp[i][j] is true, then s3[i+j-1] must be either equal to s1[i-1] or s2[j-1], or both (when s1[i-1] == s3[i+j-1] and s2[j-1] == s3[i+j-1]).

We can then fill out the rest of the dp table by iterating through all possible combinations of i and j, and checking if dp[i][j] is true using the above condition. The final result will be in dp[m][n], where m and n are the lengths of s1 and s2, respectively.

Here is the code:

```
public boolean isInterleave(String s1, String s2, String s3) {
    int m = s1.length();
    int n = s2.length();
    int t = s3.length();
    if (m + n != t) { // s1 and s2 cannot form s3 if their lengths do not add up to the length of s3
        return false;
    }
    boolean[][] dp = new boolean[m+1][n+1];
    dp[0][0] = true;
    for (int i = 1; i <= m; i++) {
        if (s1.charAt(i-1) == s3.charAt(i-1) && dp[i-1][0]) {
            dp[i][0] = true;
        }
    }
    for (int j = 1; j <= n; j++) {
        if (s2.charAt(j-1) == s3.charAt(j-1) && dp[0][j-1]) {
            dp[0][j] = true;
        }
    }
    for (int i = 1; i <= m; i++) {
        for (int j = 1; j <= n; j++) {
            if (s1.charAt(i-1) == s3.charAt(i+j-1) && dp[i-1][j]) {
                dp[i][j] = true;
            } else if (s2.charAt(j-1) == s3.charAt(i+j-1) && dp[i][j-1]) {
                dp[i][j] = true;
            }
        }
    }
    return dp[m][n];
}
